04976nam a22005895i 9780226334219DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20162016ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2015034612  a9780226334219  a(DE-B1597)525005  a(OCoLC)945663128  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aF128.68.S64bS55 2016 4aF128.68.S64bS55 2016eb 7aHIS0000002bisacsh04a700.974709/042231 aShkuda, Aaron, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Lofts of SoHo :bGentrification, Art, and Industry in New York, 1950–1980 /cAaron Shkuda. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2016] 4c©2016  a1 online resource (320 p.) :b23 halftones, 3 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aHistorical Studies of Urban America00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction Art, Artists, and Gentrifi cation -- t1. The Wastelands of New York -- t2. Making the Artist Loft -- t3. Gray Areas and Industrial Slums: The Lower Manhattan Expressway -- t4. Artist Organizations, Political Advocacy, and the Creation of a Residential SoHo -- t5. Moving Art Downtown -- t6. Real Estate and SoHo Politics: Loft Promotion and Historic Preservation in Lower Manhattan -- t7. The Embourgeoisement of SoHo -- t8. The Spread of Loft Living: Real Estate Development and Tenant Conflict in SoHo and Beyond -- t9. Making New York a Loft Living City -- tConclusion. Contemporary SoHo and the Neighborhood’s Signifi cance -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAmerican cities entered a new phase when, beginning in the 1950s, artists and developers looked upon a decaying industrial zone in Lower Manhattan and saw, not blight, but opportunity: cheap rents, lax regulation, and wide open spaces. Thus, SoHo was born. From 1960 to 1980, residents transformed the industrial neighborhood into an artist district, creating the conditions under which it evolved into an upper-income, gentrified area. Introducing the idea—still potent in city planning today—that art could be harnessed to drive municipal prosperity, SoHo was the forerunner of gentrified districts in cities nationwide, spawning the notion of the creative class. In The Lofts of SoHo, Aaron Shkuda studies the transition of the district from industrial space to artists’ enclave to affluent residential area, focusing on the legacy of urban renewal in and around SoHo and the growth of artist-led redevelopment. Shkuda explores conflicts between residents and property owners and analyzes the city’s embrace of the once-illegal loft conversion as an urban development strategy. As Shkuda explains, artists eventually lost control of SoHo’s development, but over several decades they nonetheless forced scholars, policymakers, and the general public to take them seriously as critical actors in the twentieth-century American city.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aArtist colonieszNew York (State)zNew YorkxHistoryy20th century. 0aArtistsxDwellingszNew York (State)zNew York. 0aArtistsxHousingzNew York (State)zNew York. 0aGentrificationzNew York (State)zNew York. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  asoho, gentrification, art, industry, new york, urban, neighborhood, city planning, renewal, redevelopment, artist loft, artists district, manhattan, activism, politics, advocacy, downtown, real estate, preservation, housing, wealth, nonfiction, space, revitalization, decline, deindustrialization, urbanity, tourism, fashion, trendy, architecture, factory, history.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311071098408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUrban Studies and Social R